Time Series Analysis

library(pracma)
library(lubridate)
library(tseries)

bp <- read.csv(file="bp.csv", header=TRUE, sep=",")
bp[is.na(bp)] <- 0
bp$datetime <- as_datetime(paste(bp$date, bp$time))

We analyse the data in two parts: in the first (WN), the subject was working during the week and abstained from alcohol; in the second (CA), the subject was not working, exeercised during the week, and consumed alcolhol at weekends.

wn <- bp[bp$datetime < "2019-04-18",]
ca <- bp[bp$datetime >= "2019-04-18",]

Hurst Exponent (WN)

hurstexp(wn$sys)
## Simple R/S Hurst estimation:         0.7055152 
## Corrected R over S Hurst exponent:   0.911339 
## Empirical Hurst exponent:            0.6622712 
## Corrected empirical Hurst exponent:  0.6777389

Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test (WN)

adf.test(wn$sys)
## Warning in adf.test(wn$sys): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  wn$sys
## Dickey-Fuller = -4.4389, Lag order = 5, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
adf.test(wn$dia)
## Warning in adf.test(wn$dia): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  wn$dia
## Dickey-Fuller = -5.2952, Lag order = 5, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
adf.test(wn$pulse)
## Warning in adf.test(wn$pulse): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  wn$pulse
## Dickey-Fuller = -5.0715, Lag order = 5, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

All three series are stationary.

ACF and PACF (WN)

acf(wn$sys, main="Systolic, WN")

pacf(wn$sys, main="Systolic, WN")

acf(wn$dia, main="Diastolic, WN")

pacf(wn$dia, main="Diastolic, WN")

acf(wn$pulse, main="Pulse, WN")

pacf(wn$pulse, main="Pulse, WN")

## Corrected empirical Hurst exponent:  0.7946722

hurstexp(ca$pulse)
## Simple R/S Hurst estimation:         0.6620402 
## Corrected R over S Hurst exponent:   0.7887811 
## Empirical Hurst exponent:            0.7517181 
## Corrected empirical Hurst exponent:  0.7013122 
## Theoretical Hurst exponent:          0.5545217

All these are solidly over 0.5 indicating the presence of long term memory/ persistence/ auto correlation in the series. This is what is expected from such a bio time series.
